HCIP: Unified Semiotic, Temporal, Mathematical, and Cognitive Framework
I. Temporal Diagnostic Substrate (C)
The foundational ontology of cognitive time
HCIP defines cognition as a temporally dynamic system where meaning evolves across recursive interpretive layers. The substrate consists of ten temporal primitives:
- Epoch (E₀): Activation threshold; the moment a cognitive connection forms.
- Drift (ΔC): Slow semantic migration across recursive cycles.
- Degradation (D⁻): Erosion of cognitive energy; generative entropy.
- Birth (B⁺): Emergence of new conceptual structure.
- Temporal Shear (Tₛ): Tension between fading and forming structures.
- Feed‑Forward (F→): New abstraction layers reinterpreting earlier states.
- Retroactive Reinterpretation (R↺): Later states altering the meaning of earlier states.
- Recursive Loop (τ∞): Self‑referential deepening of meaning.
- Cognitive vs Physical Time: Interpretive bidirectionality vs unidirectional physics.
- Temporal Topology:
E₀\rightarrow \Delta C\rightarrow (D⁻\vee B⁺)\rightarrow Tₛ\rightarrow F→\rightarrow R↺\rightarrow \tau \infty 
This substrate is the “physics” of HCIP — the rules governing how meaning moves.

